			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 1223 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			Here's an addendum to my previous post... and falls clearly into the "don't give suggestions" side, but I couldn't resist (and its short).<br><br>As part of class balance, it seems like there should be different "caps" for various effects in the game, where these differential caps can be used to tune various aspects of each class.  The ac soft cap (which is rumored to be almost hard for monks) is an example.  Given their low utility, it would seem reasonable and not unbalancing to increase the HASTE and WORN ATK caps for all pure melees, or providing a range of items that increase these caps so that you can tune the cap levels to a player's advancement through content.  This move would be akin to how casters can obtain increasingly effective focus items.  Items that increase the haste cap could be introduced at a fairly early raiding level (since melees with enchanters nearby can hit the haste cap with low level gear), whereas items that increase the work atk cap would not really make sense before the elemental planes or PoTime, since it isn't until then that a melee will hit the cap.	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
		<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
		 <span class=date_text>04-06-2004</span> <span class=time_text>05:32 PM</span>
		</span>
		</td>

		
			<td colspan=2 class="msg_rating_cell" valign=bottom nowrap 
			
			>
			
				&nbsp;
				
